post_text: Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker, in accordance with United States Public Law 107-89, has ordered that the United States of America flag and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts flag be lowered to half-staff at all state buildings on Friday, September 11, 2020 in observance of Patriot Day, “in honor of the individuals who lost their lives on September 11, 2001 and the Americans who made the ultimate sacrifice in the wars that followed.” The United States of America flag and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts flag shall be flown at half-staff from sunrise until sunset.

Baker has ordered that the United States of America flag and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts flag be lowered to half-staff at all state buildings on Friday, September 11, 2020, the day of interment, as a mark of solemn respect for Massachusetts State Trooper Thomas W. Devlin, who passed on September 3, 2020 as a result of injuries received in the line of duty on July 26, 2018.

This order shall be observed concurrent with the existing Commonwealth of Massachusetts half-staff notification issued in honor of Patriot Day, September 11, 2020. The United States of America flag and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts flag shall be flown at half-staff from sunrise until sunset on this day.

post_text:
What Type of Mask is OK?
All Falmouth students and staff engaging in in-person schooling will be required to wear a face mask with two-ply material.

Families are asked to provide masks for their children. If a child forgets theirs or it becomes unusable, there will be some available at school.

Acceptable
Cloth face masks
Store-bought or homemade masks are both OK. Masks with patterns need to follow school dress code.

Disposable surgical face masks
They are meant for one-time use only.

Not Acceptable
Bandanas
Loose bandanas do not prevent the spread of respiratory droplets.

Gaiters
After studying recently-released scientific data, our Health Services team has determined that gaiters may not provide sufficient protection.

Masks with valves
Valves release exhaled droplets and don’t protect others.

Face shields
CDC guidance indicates shields cannot be used as substitutes for face masks.

Be sure the mask is snug but comfortable against the sides of the face!

Compiled with information provided at https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/cloth-face-cover.html

post_text:
This a reminder that due to concerns about the effect of summer heat and traffic on the prepared meals both organizations ( schools/service center) have adjusted the meal pick up/delivery times for the summer.

Pick up times for 2 days' worth of meals will be on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 9AM-10AM. Meals will be distributed from school vans parked in front of:
East Falmouth School
Teaticket School
Mullen Hall
Staff & Volunteers will hand bags to you in your vehicles. There is no expectation to provide your name or students' names when picking up food.

If this is a new concern for your family, please contact us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us If you absolutely require delivery due to a lack of transportation, please contact us as well. We need to minimize the risk to staff/volunteers and want to make sure that delivery is an absolute necessity for your children to get fed. If you no longer require delivery, please let us know too.

Our thanks go out to you, our staff, and community members that are working together in collaboration to provide these services to our students!

Mr. Dan Whiting from Shepley Wood Products in Hyannis has very kindly and generously arranged for a plane to fly over Cape Cod on June 4th with a banner honoring the Class of 2020 from each high school on the Cape, including Falmouth High School.
Between approximately 11:15 am and 11:30 am on June 4th, the pilot will be following Route 28 over the downtown and Main Street area, then by the waterfront, and then back up Route 28 towards Bourne. The pilot is hoping to do a few laps to maximize viewing opportunities. So if you are out and about during this time on June 4th, please look up towards the sky for the Class of 2020 plane and banner!
#Classof2020flyover

The Graphics Class 3 & 4 at Falmouth High School presents
"Messages of Hope for the Class of 2020".
This project uses unconventional tools to combine images and type into a graphically designed “Message of Hope’ for the Class 2020 The project was assigned after school closings in March. While many students had no access to the graphic programs standardly used in FHS’s Graphics Class, their talent for art and design shines through in all of these pieces.
Featuring original artwork
by the following students in order of appearance
Kye DeMello
Jaiden Gaidet
Jonathan MacNevin
Gabriel Girourd
Nick Hardin
Anna Cenzalli
Riley Duarte
Isabella Ashton
Payton Manning
Parker Moulton

Augmented by Ms. Hart using Photoshop and a Wacom tablet & stylus.
Royalty-free music from BenSound: https://www.bensound.com

post_text:
Dear Staff and Families,

I write today with an important update from Governor Baker who announced during today’s press conference that schools will remain closed for the rest of this school year. Falmouth Public Schools will continue with remote learning via the Continuity of Learning Plans until June 26, 2020. The Department of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE) will be recommending districts concentrate on essential standards in addition to deeper learning of standards already taught. Our district is positioned well to follow this guidance since we began introducing new learning in our plans on April 6, 2020.

Based on this announcement of extended closure, I will provide you with additional updates as more specific plans are made for Falmouth Public Schools. We look forward to re-engaging with staff and students next week. I hope everyone stays safe and well.

Sincerely,
Lori Duerr, Ed.D.
Superintendent
Falmouth Public Schools

post_text:
Grab-and-go meals continue to be available through April vacation to district families in need. If this is a new concern for your family, please contact us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us

Pick up times for 2 days' worth of meals are Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 11am-12 noon.
Meals will be distributed from school vans parked in front of:
East Falmouth School
Teaticket School
Mullen Hall
Falmouth High School (North Falmouth, Lawrence, and Morse Pond students should consider this location)

Staff & Volunteers will hand bags to you in your vehicles. There is no expectation to provide your name or students' names when picking up food.
If you absolutely require delivery due to a lack of transportation, please contact us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us We need to minimize the risk to staff/volunteers and want to make sure that delivery is an absolute necessity for your children to get fed. If you no longer require delivery, please let us know too.

Our thanks go out to you, our staff, and community members that are working together in collaboration to provide these services to our students!

post_text:
The Falmouth Public Schools reflected on how the Clipper voyage has led us through years of growth punctuated by countless examples of achievement and success. This work allowed us to identify the parts of our history that have become traditions and the elements we want to honor and carry forward in our continued work. Then, we paused, evaluated the winds, and thought about where the journey is now leading. We considered our true north, wondered what new adventures awaited, and reoriented ourselves. We know we are yet to experience new forms of success. The result, Charting the Course to Graduation, is our vision of teaching and learning. It elevates current practice and stimulates new thinking. It demands students and teachers both navigate the way forward together as learners.

Together, we are Clippers. Yet, no matter where we go, we each can proudly reflect on our journey and affirm that our identity as a learner was shaped by our time in Falmouth. Each can say,

#IAmACLIPPER

Falmouth Emergency Preparedness
April 9 at 10:53 AM ·

An important message from Scott McGann, Health Agent for the Town of Falmouth.
" I am reaching out to you today to ask for your help in slowing the spread of the COVID-19 virus by limiting movement outside of your homes beyond what is absolutely necessary to take care of essentials. We expect to see an increase in community spread, especially over the next two weeks. If you do need to go out, we advise you to wear a mask, maintain 6 feet social distancing, and follow good hygiene practices. While there is no need for panic, we want to highlight the seriousness of the pandemic. Our community WILL benefit from your decision to take precautions."

This message was originally sent out via the Barnstable County Sheriffs Office CodeRED notification system.
#BeReadyFalmouth

Grab-and-go meals continue to be available to district families in need. If this is a new concern for your family, please contact us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us

Pick up times for 2 days' worth of meals are Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 11am-12 noon.
Meals will be distributed from school vans parked in front of:
East Falmouth School
Teaticket School
Mullen Hall
Falmouth High School (North Falmouth, Lawrence, and Morse Pond students should consider this location)

Staff & Volunteers will hand bags to you in your vehicles. There is no expectation to provide your name or students' names when picking up food.
If you absolutely require delivery due to a lack of transportation, please contact us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us We need to minimize the risk to staff/volunteers and want to make sure that delivery is an absolute necessity for your children to get fed. If you no longer require delivery, please let us know too.

Our thanks go out to you, our staff, and community members that are working together in collaboration to provide these services to our students!

Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker has ordered that the United States of America flag and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts flag be lowered to half-staff from sunrise until sunset at all state buildings on Saturday, March 21, 2020, the day of interment, in honor of US Army Private First Class Justin Candido Kirby of New Bedford, MA, who passed away on March 9, 2020 at the Fort Irwin National Training Center, Fort Irwin, California.

Private First Class Kirby will be laid to rest at the Sacred Heart Cemetery in New Bedford, MA.

Good evening, Clipper Families.

The tides have shifted once again, and we are faced with an extension to our current closure. Governor Baker made a statement only moments ago and released news of a mandatory extended period of closure, which applies to all schools in the Commonwealth. Our closure is now scheduled for three weeks, through April 7, 2020. We will continue to provide you with updates as we receive them. Tomorrow afternoon, we will release a comprehensive update with details about our closure.

Thank you and stay well.

Lori Duerr, Ed.D.
Superintendent
Falmouth Public Schools

Dear families,
To support our school community during the district's closure, we will continue to offer free breakfast and lunch meals to our qualifying students. If you would like to continue to receive free school meals for your child during the closure, please email us at info@falmouth.k12.ma.us We will begin this service on Tuesday, March 17th, meals will be available at schools each day from 11:00am-1:00pm. Please inform us in your email what school your qualifying child attends and whether you will be picking up the "grab and go" option or if you need assistance with the delivery of school meals.
Thank you and please be well.

shared_text:
YMCA Cape Cod
March 15 at 9:40 AM ·

Sunday, March 15th:
Due to the COVID-19 confirmed case on Cape Cod of the spouse of a school worker, the YMCA Cape Cod must make the difficult decision to close all programs and services for the coming week. Future closures will be determined on a weekly basis. Information will be posted on our website, Facebook page, and central phone message by noon each Friday. We know cutting off critical services such as food programs and child care for families in essential work roles puts great pressure on our community. We are actively pursuing options to provide limited services to essential workers such as health workers, first responders, and government employees, if needed. We will communicate these decisions as they are determined. Please check our website and Facebook page for updates. We thank you for your support in these unprecedented and worrisome times.

post_text:
Good morning,

I am saddened to share that we will be canceling the All Bands Night scheduled for this evening at the High School. It’s always difficult to disappoint our students and families, especially for such a wonderful event. However, to err on the side of caution, and to follow the advice set out by Town officials, we feel this is the best decision at this time. Although there is no immediate concern in Falmouth, the recommendation is to cancel large school gatherings and events that include our older population and members of our community that may have increased risk of illness.

Be assured we are considering all relevant information and making decisions daily for the safety of our students, staff, and community.

Sincerely,
Lori Duerr
